<h2>Common Mistakes That Skew Your AI SEO ROI</h2>
<p>Even with a solid calculator, these errors will distort your results:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] <strong>Counting traffic as revenue.</strong> A 50% traffic increase means nothing if conversions stay flat. Always tie metrics to business outcomes.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Ignoring assisted conversions.</strong> A customer who discovers you through a blog post and converts three months later via a brand search is still an SEO win.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Using too short a measurement window.</strong> SEO takes 6 to 12 months to show positive ROI. Measuring month-to-month creates false negatives.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Forgetting hidden costs.</strong> Agency fees, developer time, and content revisions add up. Include every dollar.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Comparing SEO to PPC directly.</strong> PPC delivers immediate, linear returns. SEO delivers delayed, compounding returns. Both have value, but their ROI curves look completely different.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Missing AI citation value.</strong> If your calculator only counts website visits, it misses 80% or more of your AI search visibility value.</li>
<li>[ ] <strong>Not segmenting by content type.</strong> Blog posts, product pages, and landing pages have different ROI profiles. Aggregate numbers hide these differences.</li>
</ul>
